    <h2 class="heading">1-26-16: Some Tips on Design</h2>
    <p>On KA, I always spend quite a bit of time on my program's design. I've decided to share some of the stuff I've learned over time. Here we go!</p>
    <ol>
        <li>I've said this before, but it really does help. Using  <code>textAlign(CENTER, CENTER);</code> both centers your text (which improves the design), and makes it easier to code. Instead of dragging the x position until you get what you want, you can just use <code>width/2</code>!</li>
        <li>Use a consistent color scheme. Try picking out one or two colors along with either black or white, and try to use just those colors for the majority of the program. For example, in <i>Solid</i>, I only used blue and white. Just throwing together a bunch of really bright colors won't look very good.</li>
        <li>Use transparency to spice things up. What I mean by this is putting a drop shadow or a transparent triangle on half of a square makes it look better than just a square. For example, in <i>Mega Mine</i>, Thunder did a good job of adding little shadows to the dirt blocks. This might not seem to do much, but it's often the details that make a game better than the rest.</li>
        <li>Spend some time making a neat background. People usually do enjoy a cool background more than just <code>background(0);</code>. If you don't have time to make a cool background, ask around KA. There's users who like to do that sort of thing (you could start with KingKhan007, AlexT, myself, or Blaze). A good example of doing this would be in the game</li>
    </ol>
    <p>Hope this article helps!</p>
    
